User survey for ImagingSociety 2025 - National MRI research infrastructure in Norway

Author

Dr. Athanasia M. Mowinckel

Published

September 30, 2025

Background

This report presents an analysis of the survey data collected for the national grant scheme application for MRI research infrastructure in Norway. The survey was designed to gather insights from the research community on the current use, needs, and challenges related to MRI for human research.

The following sections will present a summary of the key findings, including graphical representations of the quantitative data and a textual summary of the open-ended responses, with the help of the Gemini LMM.

Survey Results

Of the 63 responses, 28 participants reported they currently use MRI for research, 44% indicate a future interest in using the new MRI facility for their work.

Participant Demographics

This section provides an overview of the survey participants’ roles and institutions.

Research Areas

The survey respondents represent a diverse range of research areas, with a strong emphasis on cognitive neuroscience and related fields. Key themes include:

  • Cognitive Neuroscience: A dominant area, encompassing attention, decision-making, learning, predictive processing, language, and music cognition.
  • Neuroscience: A broad category including general neuroscience, integrative neuroscience, affective/social/political neuroscience, and brain connectivity.
  • Mental Health & Disorders: A significant focus, covering mental disorders, psychotherapy, child and adolescent psychiatry, psychosis, anxiety, anorexia nervosa, and mood disorders.
  • Aging & Dementia: Another prominent area, with research on healthy aging, dementia, cerebrovascular disease, and Alzheimer’s disease.
  • Brain Injury: Including research on brain injury in sport and rehabilitation medicine.
  • Neurology & Neurodegenerative Diseases: Research on multiple sclerosis, neurodegenerative diseases, stroke, and epilepsy.
  • Women’s Health: Including research on sexual health, body image, menopause, menstrual cycle, and aging cognition.
  • Methodological Approaches: Employing various methods such as MRI (structural, functional, microstructural), EEG, fNIRS, pupillometry, eye-tracking, computational modelling, and qualitative research.

There is also representation in:

  • Autoimmunity (specifically Lupus)
  • Pain Research
  • Speech and Language Processing
  • Impulse control and dopamine
  • Paleoclimatology (using medical imaging)
  • Psychophysiology
  • Human Computer Interaction
  • Environmental Psychology
  • Ophthalmology (Cerebral Visual Impairments)
  • MR Spectroscopy
  • Spinal Cord MRI
  • Brain Tumours
  • Smell and Taste
  • Systems Immunology
  • Network Neuroscience

How MRI Would Enhance Research

Access to MRI is crucial for a significant portion of the respondents’ research, with many highlighting its current limitations and the potential for substantial improvements in their work with increased availability, affordability, and better access to high-quality MRI resources. Specifically, expanded MRI access would:

  • Enable a wider range of research topics: Including studies on sexual dysfunction, bilingualism and aging, pain, ADHD in women, dementia, eating disorders, neurological disorders, musculoskeletal and solid-state whole-body tumors, geohazards, the menstrual cycle, and the development of novel MRI sequences and methods.
  • Improve research quality and scope: By allowing for larger participant sample sizes, more comprehensive data collection, and the ability to track brain changes throughout the lifespan.
  • Facilitate translational research: By providing clinically relevant information for decision-making, disease tracking, and the development of novel algorithms for use in hospital settings and image-guided neurosurgery.
  • Support collaborative research: By enabling participation in multicenter studies, both nationally and internationally.
  • Open new research avenues: For those currently lacking access or experience, enabling the use of fMRI to study brain networks, assess the impact of interventions on the brain, and integrate neuroimaging data with other methods.
  • Strengthen existing research programs: by allowing for more reliable, stable, and predictable access to scanning facilities.
  • Improve diagnosis and treatment: Through identification of biomarkers and increased ability to diagnose diseases such as MS and epilepsy
  • Enhance research careers: Making researchers more competitive for grants and publications.

The key challenges mentioned were limited availability, high costs, lack of trained personnel, dependence on clinical scanners, and difficulties with data sharing and collaboration. Addressing these challenges would significantly boost the potential of MRI-based research across diverse fields.

Future Needs

This section analyzes which conditions are considered most important for the future of MRI research in Norway.

Summary of Free-text Comments

This section provides a summary of the open-ended comments, generated using the Gemini LMM.

Several key themes emerge from the responses. A strong desire exists for increased accessibility and prioritization of MRI resources for research, potentially through reduced costs and dedicated research scanners outside of the hospital environment, closer to university campuses. This would facilitate novel experimental designs and alleviate competition with clinical needs. Furthermore, respondents emphasized the importance of fostering a collaborative MRI research community, potentially encompassing multiple sites and benefiting from the expertise of individuals like Karsten Specht and initiatives like MMIV. Ensuring consistency in capabilities across different sites is crucial, alongside establishing routinely available and accessible scanning hours specifically for researchers. Finally, the need for specialized resources like a 7T scanner for advanced subcortical research was highlighted, and the potential for a national network of synchronized scanners to enable population-level brain mapping, drawing inspiration from the UK Biobank model, was proposed.

Conclusion

In conclusion, the overwhelming sentiment expressed in this survey underscores a critical need for increased access to dedicated research-focused MRI scanners in Norway. The diverse range of researchers, spanning various disciplines and institutions across the country, articulated significant limitations imposed by the current infrastructure. From hindered project timelines and sample sizes to the inability to pursue novel research avenues and participate in multi-center collaborations, the lack of readily available research MRI capacity is demonstrably impeding scientific progress. The survey participants highlighted that a dedicated research scanner would enhance the quality of research & size of participant samples and enable them to plan and conduct well-powered imaging studies. Furthermore, the identified need for expert personnel, such as MRI physicists and neuroradiologists, further emphasizes the importance of a comprehensive, well-supported research infrastructure. Addressing these deficiencies by investing in additional research MRI scanners and their associated resources will not only unlock the vast potential of Norwegian researchers but also position Norway at the forefront of international neuroimaging research, ultimately benefiting the health and well-being of its population.
